Firewalls, controlling what can reach you.

A firewall decides which network packets the kernel accepts and which it quietly drops. On linux the firewall is built right into the kernel, and userspace tools simply tell it which rules to apply. It helps to picture three layers in the modern stack. At the bottom is n-f-tables, the kernel module that actually does the filtering, which supersedes the older eye-p-tables. Eye-p-tables is the older interface, still common and still working, and on most distributions it now runs as a translation layer on top of n-f-tables. And on top of all that sit the friendly high-level tools, you-eff-double-you on the debian family and firewall-d on the red hat family, which generate the underlying rules for you. Those friendly tools are what you will actually use day to day.

Take you-eff-double-you, the uncomplicated firewall. By default it denies incoming connections and allows outgoing ones. You check its state with you-eff-double-you status, turn it on with enable and off with disable. You allow traffic by service name, for example allowing s-s-h, or by port and protocol, or only from a particular network or source address. You can explicitly deny something, list the rules with numbers, and delete a rule by its number, or reset everything back to nothing.

There is one absolutely critical warning here, and it is the classic way people lock themselves out of a cloud machine: before you enable the firewall, allow s-s-h. If you enable a default-deny firewall on a remote box without first permitting the very port you are connected through, you will cut your own connection and be unable to get back in. The red hat family's firewall-d works a little differently, organising rules into zones, where each interface is assigned to a zone and that zone's rules govern its traffic, but the same caution applies. For the exam, know you-eff-double-you and firewall-d at the user level, and merely recognise eye-p-tables and n-f-tables syntax when you see it in older documentation.
